content:
To test a model’s ability to make predictions, Einstein Discovery uses k-fold cross-validation, a process that reduces sampling bias when validating a model. This tab summarizes the results of the cross-validation process for this model.

Navigate to the Cross Validation Tab

In Performance, click Model Evaluation, then Cross Validation.

The following table describes the columns in the Cross Validation tab:

COLUMN NAME	DESCRIPTION
Metric Name	Name of the metric.
Training Set	Metrics for the set of observations used to train the model.
Validation Set	Metrics for the set of observations used to validate predictions.
Fold #1 through Fold #4 Metrics for each fold.

The following table describes the metrics in the Cross Validation tab:

METRIC NAME	DESCRIPTION
Number of Rows	Total number of observations.
AUC	Area Under the Curve. Represents correct classification by a logistic model.
GINI	Quantifies how close the obtained model performs to a theoretically best possible model.
Log Loss	Measures model performance on a scale of 0–1, where 0 represents a perfect model.
Mean Per Class Error	Measures how often predictions are wrong.

Einstein Discovery conducts k-fold cross-validation (k=4) by randomly dividing observations into four separate partitions and conducting test passes. Model metrics are compiled for each fold and the average is taken for an overall score.
title: Cross-Validation in Einstein Discovery
